 | footer = LaVeyan Satanism's views on human nature are influenced by the work of [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] and [[Ayn Rand]].
}}

For LaVey, the human being was explicitly viewed as an animal,{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=4|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288|3a1=Baddeley|3y=2010|3p=74|4a1=Lap|4y=2013|4p=94}} who thus has no purpose other than [[survival of the fittest]], and who therefore exists in an [[amorality|amoral]] context.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} He believed that in adopting a philosophical belief in its own superiority above that of the other animals, humankind has become "the most vicious animal of all".{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=94}} For LaVey, non-human animals and children represent an ideal, "the purest form of carnal existence", because they have not been indoctrinated with Christian or other religious concepts of guilt and shame.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=95}} His ethical views focused around placing oneself and one's family before others, minding one's own business, and &ndash; for men &ndash; behaving like a [[gentleman]].{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}} In responding to threats and harm, he promoted a policy of ''[[Eye for an eye|lex talionis]]'', for instance reversing a Biblical Christian teaching by stating that "if a man smite thee on the one cheek, ''smash'' him on the other."{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}} 

LaVeyan Satanism places great emphasis on the role of [[liberty]] and personal freedom.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=322}} LaVey believed that the ideal Satanist should be individualistic and non-conformist, rejecting what he called the "colorless existence" that mainstream society sought to impose on those living within it.{{sfn|Dyrendal|2013|p=129}} He rejected [[consumerism]] and what he called the "death cult" of [[fashion]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=374}} He praised the human [[Ego (Freudian)|ego]] for encouraging an individual's pride, self-respect, and self-realization and accordingly believed in satisfying the ego's desires.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=92}} He expressed the view that self-indulgence was a desirable trait,{{sfn|Maxwell-Stuart|2011|p=198}} and that hate and aggression were not wrong or undesirable emotions but that they were necessary and advantageous for survival.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=94}} Accordingly, he praised the [[Seven Deadly Sins]] as virtues which were beneficial for the individual.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Schipper|2y=2010|2p=107}}

Similarly, LaVey criticized the negative and restrictive attitude to sexuality present in many religions, instead supporting any sexual acts that take place between consenting adults.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=91|3a1=Faxneld|3a2=Petersen|3y=2014|3p=168|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=321}} His Church welcomed homosexual members from its earliest years,{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=168}} and he also endorsed celibacy for those who were [[asexuality|asexual]].{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=168}} He sought to discourage negative feelings of guilt arising from sexual acts such as masturbation and fetishes,{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=91}} and believed that rejecting these sexual inhibitions and guilt would result in a happier and healthier society.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=169}} Discussing women, LaVey argued that they should use sex as a tool to manipulate men, in order to advance their own personal power.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2014|p=170}} Conversely, non-consensual sexual relations, such as [[rape]] and [[child sexual abuse|child molestation]], were denounced by LaVey and his Church.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=288|2a1=Maxwell-Stuart|2y=2011|2p=198}}

LaVey believed in the imminent demise of Christianity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=357}} In addition, he believed that society would enter an Age of Satan, in which a generation living in accordance with LaVeyan principles would come to power.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=379}}
LaVey supported [[eugenics]] and expected it to become a necessity in the future, when it would be used to breed an elite who reflected LaVey's "Satanic" principles.{{sfnm|1a1=Lap|1y=2013|1p=95|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=376}} In his view, this elite would be "superior people" who displayed the "Satanic" qualities of creativity and nonconformity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=376}} He regarded these traits as capable of hereditary transmission, and made the claim that "Satanists are born, not made".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=376}} He believed that the elite should be siphoned off from the rest of the human "herd", with the latter being forced into ghettoes, ideally "space ghettoes" located on other planets.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=375}}
The anthropologist Jean La Fontaine highlighted an article that appeared in a LaVeyan magazine, ''The Black Flame'', in which one writer described "a true Satanic society" as one in which the population consists of "free-spirited, well-armed, fully-conscious, self-disciplined individuals, who will neither need nor tolerate any external entity 'protecting' them or telling them what they can and cannot do."{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} This rebellious approach conflicts with LaVey's firm beliefs in observing the [[rule of law]].{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} Although personally neither a [[fascism|fascist]] nor [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]],{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=373}} LaVey was on good terms with various neo-Nazi and other right-wing groups operating in the United States.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=368}}

===Magic===
{{main|Greater and lesser magic}}

[[File:Aleister Crowley.jpg|thumb|right|150px|LaVey's understanding of magic was influenced by the British occultist Aleister Crowley ]]

Although LaVey's ideas were largely shaped around a secular and scientific world-view, he also expressed a belief in [[magic (paranormal)|magic]].{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1pp=3–4|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=336}} Rather than characterising magic as a [[supernatural]] phenomenon, LaVey expressed the view that it was a part of the natural world thus far undiscovered by scientists.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|pp=3–4}} Outlined in ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey defined magic as "the change in situations or events in accordance with one's will, which would, using normally accepted methods, be unchangeable",{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1pp=288&ndash;289|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2p=95|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=96|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=342}} a definition that reflects the influence of the British occultist [[Aleister Crowley]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=342}} Although he never explained exactly how he believed that this magical process worked,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}} LaVey stated that magicians could successfully utilise this magical force through intensely imagining their desired goal and thus directing the force of their own willpower toward it.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=4|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=339}} He emphasised the idea that magical forces could be manipulated through "purely emotional" rather than intellectual acts.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}} 

This practice puts LaVeyan Satanism within a wider tradition of 'high magic' or ceremonial magic,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=339}} and has also been compared with [[Christian Science]] and [[Scientology]].{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} LaVey adopted beliefs and ideas from older magicians but consciously de-Christianised and Satanised them for his own purposes.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=337}}
In presenting himself as applying a scientific perspective on magic, LaVey was likely influenced by Crowley, who had also presented his approach to magic in the same way.{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=376}} However, in contrast to many older ceremonial magicians, LaVey denied that there was any division between [[black magic]] and [[white magic]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=Dyrendal|2y=2012|2p=377|3a1=Dyrendal|3a2=Petersen|3a3=Lewis|3y=2016|3p=86}} attributing this dichotomy purely to the "smug hypocrisy and self-deceit" of those who called themselves "white magicians".{{sfn|Dyrendal|2012|p=377}} He similarly differed from many older magicians who emphasised magic as a practice designed to bring about personal transformation and transcendence; rather, for LaVey magic was employer for material gain, personal influence, to harm enemies, and to gain success in love and sex.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=336–337}}

LaVey defined his system of magic as [[greater and lesser magic]].{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=289|2a1=Petersen|2y=2012|2pp=95–96|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=97|4a1=Dyrendal|4a2=Lewis|4a3=Petersen|4y=2016|4p=86}} Greater magic is a form of ritual practice and is meant as psychodramatic catharsis to focus one's emotional energy for a specific purpose. These rites are based on three major psycho-emotive themes: ''compassion'' ([[love]]), ''destruction'' (hate), and ''sex'' (lust).{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=86}} The space in which a ritual is performed is known as an "intellectual decompression chamber",{{sfn|The Invention of Satanism Dyrendal, Petersen|2016|page=89}} where skepticism and disbelief are willfully suspended, thus allowing the magicians to fully express their mental and emotional needs, holding back nothing regarding their deepest feelings and desires. This magic could then be employed to ensure sexual gratification, material gain, personal success, or to curse one's enemies.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=289}} LaVey also wrote of "the balance factor", insisting that any magical aims should be realistic.{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=98}} These rituals are often considered to be magical acts,{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} with LaVey's Satanism encouraging the practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]] to aid one's selfish ends.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=21}} Much of Satanic ritual is designed for an individual to carry out alone; this is because concentration is seen as key to performing magical acts.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=98–99}}

Lesser magic, also referred to an "everyday" or "situational" magic, is the practice of manipulation by means of applied psychology. LaVey defined it as "wile and guile obtained through various devices and contrived situations, which when utilized, can create change in accordance with one's will."{{sfn|Witchcraft and Magic in Europe, Volume 6: The Twentieth Century|Blecourt, Hutton, Fontaine|1999|p=91}} LaVey wrote that a key concept in lesser magic is the “command to look”, which can be accomplished by utilizing elements of “sex, sentiment, and wonder”,{{sfn|Controversial New Religions|Lewis, Petersen|p=418}} in addition to the utilization of looks, body language, scents,{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|page=97}} color, patters, and odor.{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2014|p=90}} This system encourages a form of manipulative role-play, wherein the practitioner may alter several elements of their physical appearance in order to aid them in seducing or "bewitching" on object of desire.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}}

LaVey developed “The Synthesizer Clock”, the purpose of which is to divide humans into distinct groups of people based primarily on body shape and personality traits.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} The synthesizer is modeled as a clock, and based on concepts of [[somatotypes]].{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Petersen|2010|p=67}} The clock is intended to aid a witch in identifying themselves, subsequently aiding in utilizing the “attraction of opposites” to “spellbind” the witch's object of desire by assuming the opposite role.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} The successful application of lesser magic is said to be built upon one's understanding of their place on the clock.{{sfn|Sexuality and New Religious Movements|Lewis, Bogdan|2014|p=}} Upon finding your position on the clock, you are encouraged to adapt it as seen fit, and perfect your type by harmonizing its element for better success.{{sfn|The Devil's Party: Satanism in Modernity|Faxneld, Petersen|2013|p=97}} Dyrendal referred to LaVey's techniques as “[[Erving Goffman]] meets [[William Mortensen]]”.{{sfn|Controversial New Religions|Lewis, Petersen|2014|page=418}} Drawing insights from psychology, biology, and sociology,{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2010|p=89}} Petersen noted that lesser magic combines occult and “rejected sciences of body analysis [and] temperaments.”{{sfn|Handbook of Religion and the Authority of Science|Lewis, Hammer|2010|p=68}}

==Basic tenets==

The "central convictions" of LaVeyan Satanism are formulated into three lists, which are regularly reproduced within the Church of Satan's written material.{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=431}}

===The Nine Satanic Statements===
[[File:Brimstone.gif|thumb|right|150px|The [[alchemical symbol]] for [[Sulfur]], as it appears in ''The Satanic Bible'' above the Nine Satanic Statements.]]
''The Nine Satanic Statements'' are a set of nine assertions made by LaVey in the introductory chapters of ''The Satanic Bible''. They are considered a touchstone of contemporary organized Satanism that constitute, in effect, brief aphorisms that capture Satanic philosophy.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=192}} The first three statements touch on “indulgence”, “vital existence” and “undefiled wisdom” which presents a positive view of the Satanist as a carnal, physical and pragmatic being, where enjoyment of physical existence and an undiluted view of this-worldly truth are promoted as the core values of Satanism, combining elements of Darwinism and Epicureanism. Statement four, five and six deal in matters of ethics, through “kindness to those who deserve it”, “vengeance” and “responsibility to the responsible”, painting a harsh picture of society and human relations by emphasizing justice rather than love. Statements seven, eight and nine reject the dignity of man, sin and the Christian church. Humans are characterized as “just another animal”, traditional “sins” are promoted as means for gratification, and religion as mere business. The adversarial and [[Antinomy|antinomian]] aspect of Satan takes precedence in support of statements four through nine, with non-conformity being presented as a core ideal.{{sfn|Petersen|2011|pp=159-160}}

# Satan represents [[Pleasure|indulgence]] instead of [[abstinence]].
# Satan represents [[Self-preservation|vital existence]] instead of [[Delusion|spiritual pipe dreams]].
# Satan represents [[Perspicacity|undefiled wisdom]] instead of hypocritical [[Self-deception|self-deceit]].
# Satan represents [[Unconditional love#Conditional love|kindness to those who deserve it]], instead of [[Unconditional love|love wasted on ingrates]].
# Satan represents [[Revenge|vengeance]] instead of [[turning the other cheek]].
# Satan represents [[Accountability|responsibility to the responsible]] instead of concern for [[Victim playing|psychic vampires]].
# Satan represents man as just another animal who, because of his "[[Anthropocentrism|divine spiritual and intellectual development]]", has become the [[Human–wildlife conflict|most vicious animal of all]].
# Satan represents all of the [[Seven deadly sins|so-called sins]], as they all lead to physical, mental, or emotional gratification.
# Satan has been the best friend the [[Christian Church|Church]] has ever had, as he has kept it in business all these years.</small>{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1pp=191&ndash;192|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=71|3a1=Van Luijk|3y=2016|3p=297}}

===The Eleven Satanic Rules of the Earth===

# Do not give opinions or advice unless you are asked.
# Do not tell your troubles to others unless you are sure they want to hear them.
# When in another's lair, show them respect or else do not go there.
# If a guest in your lair annoys you, treat them cruelly and without mercy.
# Do not make sexual advances unless you are given the mating signal.
# Do not take that which does not belong to you unless it is a burden to the other person and they cry out to be relieved.
# Acknowledge the power of magic if you have employed it successfully to obtain your desires. If you deny the power of magic after having called upon it with success, you will lose all you have obtained.
# Do not complain about anything to which you need not subject yourself.
# Do not harm little children.
# Do not kill non-human animals unless you are attacked or for your food.
# When walking in open territory, bother no one. If someone bothers you, ask them to stop. If they do not stop, destroy them.{{sfn|Drury|2003|pp=192&ndash;193}}

==Rites and practices==

===Rituals and ceremonies===

LaVey emphasized that in his tradition, Satanic rites came in two forms, neither of which were acts of worship; in his terminology, "rituals" were intended to bring about change, whereas "ceremonies" celebrated a particular occasion.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=98|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=97}} These rituals were often considered to be magical acts,{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} with LaVey's Satanism encouraging the practice of [[Magic (paranormal)|magic]] to aid one's selfish ends.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=21}} Much of LaVeyan ritual is designed for an individual to carry out alone; this is because concentration is seen as key to performing magical acts.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=98–99}} In ''The Satanic Bible'', LaVey described three types of ritual in his religion: sex rituals designed to attract the desired romantic or sexual partner, compassionate rituals with the intent of helping people (including oneself), and destructive magic which seeks to do harm to others.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} In designing these rituals, LaVey drew upon a variety of older sources, with scholar of Satanism Per Faxneld noting that LaVey "assembled rituals from a hodgepodge of historical sources, literary as well as esoteric".{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=88}}

[[File:Baphomet.png|thumb|left|[[Eliphas Levi]]'s image of [[Baphomet]] is embraced by LaVeyan Satanists as a symbol of duality, fertility, and the "powers of darkness", serving as the namesake of their primary insignia, [[The Sigil of Baphomet]].]]

LaVey described a number of rituals in his book, ''[[The Satanic Rituals]]''; these are "dramatic performances" with specific instructions surrounding the clothing to be worn, the music to be used, and the actions to be taken.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} This attention to detail in the design of the rituals was intentional, with their pageantry and theatricality intending to engage the participants' senses and aesthetic sensibilities at various levels and enhancing the participants' willpower for magical ends.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|pp=97, 98}} LaVey prescribed that male participants should wear black robes, while older women should wear black, and other women should dress attractively in order to stimulate sexual feelings among many of the men.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} All participants are instructed to wear amulets of either the upturned pentagram or the image of [[Baphomet]].{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}}

According to LaVey's instructions, on the altar is to be placed an image of Baphomet. This should be accompanied by various candles, all but one of which are to be black. The lone exception is to be a white candle, used in destructive magic, which is kept to the right of the altar.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} Also to be included are a bell which is rung nine times at the start and end of the ceremony, a chalice made of anything but gold, and which contains an alcoholic drink symbolizing the "Elixir of Life", a sword that represents aggression, a model phallus used as an [[aspergillum]], a gong, and parchment on which requests to Satan are to be written before being burned.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}} Although alcohol was consumed in the church's rites, [[drunkenness]] was frowned upon and the taking of illicit drugs was forbidden.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}}

LaVeyan rituals sometimes include anti-Christian blasphemies, which are intended to have a liberating effect on the participants.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=98}}
In some of the rituals, a naked woman serves as the altar; in these cases it is made explicit that the woman's body itself becomes the altar, rather than have her simply lying on an existing altar.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}} In contrast to longstanding stereotypes about Satanists, there is no place for sexual orgies in LaVeyan ritual.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=97|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=337}} Neither animal nor human sacrifice takes place.{{sfnm|1a1=La Fontaine|1y=1999|1p=97|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=338}} Children are banned from attending these rituals, with the only exception being the Satanic Baptism, which is specifically designed to involve infants.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=97}}

LaVey also developed his own [[Black Mass]], which was designed as a form of deconditioning to free the participant from any inhibitions that they developed living in Christian society.{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2012|1pp=96&ndash;97|2a1=Faxneld|2y=2013|2p=76|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=98}} He noted that in composing the Black Mass rite, he had drawn upon the work of the French fiction writers [[Charles Baudelaire]] and [[Joris-Karl Huysmans]].{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=86}} LaVey openly toyed with the use of literature and popular culture in other rituals and ceremonies, thus appealing to artifice, pageantry, and showmanship.{{sfn|Petersen|2012|pp=106&ndash;107}} For instance, he published an outline of a ritual which he termed the "Call to Cthulhu" which drew upon the stories of the alien god [[Cthulhu]] authored by American horror writer [[H. P. Lovecraft]]. In this rite, set to take place at night in a secluded location near to a turbulent body of water, a celebrant takes on the role of Cthulhu and appears before the assembled Satanists, signing a pact between them in the language of Lovecraft's fictional "Old Ones".{{sfn|Petersen|2012|p=106}}

===Holidays===
{{main|Satanic holidays}}

LaVey and the Church of Satan deemed an individual's birthday to be the most important day of the year.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=50|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288|3a1=Lap|3y=2013|3p=99|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=330}} [[Walpurgisnacht]] (April 30) is celebrated as the date on which LaVey founded his Church.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1pp=50&ndash;51|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288}} A third annual festival is [[Halloween]], which also has associations with magic and dark entities.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=51|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=288}}

===Symbolism===
[[Image:SamaelLilithGoatPentagram.png|thumb|right|The Sigil of Baphomet]]
As a symbol of his Satanic church, LaVey adopted the upturned five-pointed pentagram.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=26}} The upturned pentagram had previously been used by the French occultist [[Eliphas Lévi]], and had been adopted by his disciple, [[Stanislas de Guaita]], who merged it with a goat's head in his 1897 book, ''Key of Black Magic''.{{sfn|Medway|2001|p=26}} In the literature and imagery predating LaVey, imagery used to represent the "satanic" is denoted by inverted crosses and blasphemous parodies of Christian art. The familiar goat's head inside an inverted pentagram did not become the foremost symbol of Satanism until the founding of the Church of Satan in 1966.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=20}} LaVey learned of this variant of the symbol after it had been reproduced on the front cover of Maurice Bessy's [[coffee table book]], ''Pictorial History of Magic and the Supernatural''.{{sfnm|1a1=Medway|1y=2001|1p=26|2a1=Lewis|2y=2001b|2p=20}} Feeling that this symbol embodied his philosophy, LaVey decided to adopt it for his Church.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=20}} In its formative years, the church utilized this image on its membership cards, stationary, medallions and most notably above the altar in the ritual chamber of the Black House.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}}

During the writing of ''The Satanic Bible'', it was decided that a unique version of the symbol should be rendered to be identified exclusively with the church. LaVey created a new version of Guaita's image, one which was geometrically precise, with two perfect circles surrounding the pentagram, the goat head redrawn, and the Hebrew lettering altered to look more serpentine.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}} LaVey had this design copyrighted to the church,{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=21}} claiming authorship under the pseudonym of "Hugo Zorilla".{{sfn|Partridge|2005|p=376}} In doing so, the symbol &ndash; which came to be known as the [[Sigil of Baphomet]]{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2001b|1p=20|2a1=Partridge|2y=2005|2p=376}} &ndash; came to be closely associated with Satanism in the public imagination.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=20}}

==History==

===Origins: 1966–72===
Although there were forms of religious Satanism that predated the creation of LaVeyan Satanism—namely those propounded by [[Stanisław Przybyszewski]] and [[Ben Kadosh]]—these had no unbroken lineage of succession to LaVey's form.{{sfn|Faxneld|2013|p=75}} For this reason, the sociologist of religion [[Massimo Introvigne]] stated that "with few exceptions, LaVey is at the origins of all contemporary Satanism".{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=299}} Similarly, the historian Ruben van Luijk claimed that the creation of LaVeyan Satanism marked "the actual beginning of Satanism as a religion such as it is practiced in the world today".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=297}}

After he came to public attention, LaVey shielded much of his early life in secrecy, and little is known about it for certain.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=295}} He had been born in [[Chicago]] as Howard Stanton Levey in either March or April 1930.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=51|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=300}} He was of mixed Ukrainian, Russian, and German ancestry.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=51}} He claimed to have worked in the [[circus]] and [[carnival]] in the years following the [[Second World War]],{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=301}} and in later years, he also alleged that he worked at the San Francisco Orchestra, although this never existed.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=301}} He also claimed to have had a relationship with a young [[Marilyn Monroe]], although this too was untrue.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=300–301}} 

By the 1960s he was living at 6114 California Street in San Francisco, a house that he had inherited from his parents.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=294, 296}} He took an interest in occultism and amassed a large collection of books on the subject.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} At some point between 1957 and 1960 he began hosting classes at his house every Friday in which lectures on occultism and other subjects were given.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=52}} Among the topics covered were [[freak]]s, [[extra-sensory perception]], [[Spiritualism]], [[cannibalism]], and historical methods of [[torture]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} An informal group established around these lectures, which came to be known as the Magic Circle.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=52|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=296}} Among those affiliated with this gathering were the filmmaker and [[Thelema|Thelemite]] occultist [[Kenneth Anger]],{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}} and the anthropologist [[Michael Harner]], who later established the [[core shamanism]] movement.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}}

LaVey likely began preparations for the formation of his [[Church of Satan]] in either 1965 or early 1966,{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=52}} and it was officially founded on [[Walpurgisnacht]] 1966.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=Gardell|2y=2003|2p=285|3a1=Baddeley|3y=2010|3p=71|4a1=Dyrendal|4a2=Lewis|4a3=Petersen|4y=2016|4p=52}} He then declared that 1966 marked Year One of the new Satanic era.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=297}} It was the first organized church in modern times to be devoted to the figure of Satan,{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=5}} and according to Faxneld and Petersen, the church represented "the first public, highly visible, and long-lasting organisation which propounded a coherent satanic discourse".{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=81}} Its early members were the attendees of LaVey's Magic Circle, although it soon began attracting new recruits.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}} Many of these individuals were sadomasochists or homosexuals, attracted by the LaVeyan openness to different sexual practices.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=346}} LaVey had painted his house black,{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} with it becoming known as "the [[Black House (Church of Satan)|Black House]]",{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2005|1p=428|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2pp=66, 71|3a1=Dyrendal|3a2=Lewis|3a3=Petersen|3y=2016|3p=53}} and it was here that weekly rituals were held every Friday night.{{sfn|Dyrendal|Lewis|Petersen|2016|p=53}} 

LaVey played up to his Satanic associations by growing a pointed beard and wearing a black cloak and inverted pentagram.{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=188}} He added to his eccentric persona by obtaining unusual pets, including a lion that was kept caged in his back garden.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=296}} Describing himself as the "High Priest of Satan",{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=197}} LaVey defined his position within the church as "monarchical in nature, papal in degree and absolute in power".{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} He led the churches' governing Council of Nine,{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} and implemented a system of five initiatory levels that the LaVeyan Satanist could advance through by demonstrating their knowledge of LaVeyan philosophy and their personal accomplishments in life.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} These were known as Apprentice Satanist I°, Witch or Warlock II°, Priest or Priestess of Mendes III°, Magister IV°, and Magus V°.{{sfn|Drury|2003|p=197}} 

{{Quote box
| title = 
| quote = Never one for theory, LaVey created a belief system somewhere between religion, philosophy, psychology, and carnival (or circus), freely appropriating science, mythology, fringe beliefs, and play in a potent mix. The core goal was always indulgence and vital existence, based on the devices and desires of the self-made man.
| source = — Per Faxneld and Jesper Petersen.{{sfn|Faxneld|Petersen|2013|p=79}}
| align = left
| width = 30em
