}}

The church experienced its "golden age" from 1966 to 1972, when it had a strong media presence.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=136}}  In February 1967, LaVey held a much publicized Satanic wedding, which was followed by the Satanic baptism of his daughter Zeena in May, and then a Satanic funeral in December.{{sfnm|1a1=Petersen|1y=2005|1p=438|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=71|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3p=309|4a1=van Luijk|4y=2016|4p=297}} Another publicity-attracting event was the "Topless Witch Revue", a nightclub show held on San Francisco's North Beach; the use of topless women to attract attention alienated a number of the church's early members.{{sfnm|1a1=Dyrendal|1a2=Lewis|1a3=Petersen|1y=2016|1p=54|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=346}} Through these and other activities, he soon attracted international media attention, being dubbed "the Black Pope".{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=71}} He also attracted a number of celebrities to join his Church, most notably [[Sammy Davis Junior]] and [[Jayne Mansfield]].{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=286|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=72|3a1=Schipper|3y=2010|3pp=105&ndash;106}} LaVey also established branches of the church, known as ''grottos'', in various parts of the United States.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=74}} He may have chosen the term ''grotto'' over ''[[coven]]'' because the latter term had come to be used by practitioners of the modern Pagan religion of [[Wicca]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=344}} These included the Babylon Grotto in [[Detroit]], the Stygian Grotto in [[Dayton]], and the Lilith Grotto in [[New York City]].{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=74}} In 1971, a Dutch follower of LaVey's, Maarten Lamers, established his own Kerk van Satan grotto in [[Amsterdam]].{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=519|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=344–345}}

As a result of the success of the film ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' and the concomitant growth of interest in Satanism, an editor at [[Avon Books]], Peter Mayer, approached LaVey and commissioned him to write a book, which became ''[[The Satanic Bible]]''.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=8|2a1=Baddeley|2y=2010|2p=72}} While part of the text was LaVey's original writing, other sections of the book consisted of direct quotations from [[Arthur Desmond]]'s right-wing tract ''[[Might is Right]]'' and the occultist [[Aleister Crowley]]'s version of [[John Dee]]'s ''Enochian Keys''.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=8|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=315}} There is evidence that LaVey was inspired by the writings of the American philosopher [[Ayn Rand]]; and while accusations that he plagiarized her work in ''The Satanic Bible'' have been denied by one author, {{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=9}} Chris Mathews stated that "LaVey stole selectively and edited lightly" and that his "Satanism at times closely parallels Ayn Rand's [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivist philosophy]]."<ref>Matthews, Chris. ''Modern Satanism: Anatomy of a Radical Subculture'', Praeger Publishers, 2009, p. 65-66</ref> The book ''The Satanic Bible'' served to present LaVey's ideas to a far wider audience than they had previously had.{{sfn|Baddeley|2010|p=72}} In 1972, he published a sequel, ''The Satanic Rituals''.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=298}} 

LaVey's Church emerged at a point in American history when Christianity was on the decline as many of the nation's youth broke away from their parental faith and explored alternative systems of religiosity.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=298}} The milieu in which LaVey's Church was operating was dominated by the [[counterculture of the 1960s]]; his Church reflected some of its concerns &ndash; free love, alternative religions, freedom from church and state &ndash; but ran contrary to some of the counterculture's other main themes, such as peace and love, compassion, and the use of mind-altering drugs.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=295|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=298}} He expressed condemnation of the [[hippies]]; in one ritual he hung an image of [[Timothy Leary]] upside down while stamping on a tablet of [[LSD]].{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=299}}

===Later development: 1972&ndash;present===

[[File:Karla LaVey.jpg|right|thumb|Karla LaVey, founder of the First Satanic Church, in 2012]]

LaVey ceased conducting group rituals and workshops in his home in 1972.{{sfnm|1a1=Lap|1y=2013|1p=84|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=345}}
In 1973, church leaders in Michigan, Ohio, and Florida split to form their own Church of Satanic Brotherhood, however this disbanded in 1974 when one of its founders publicly converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} Subsequently, Church members based in Kentucky and Indiana left to found the [[Ordo Templi Satanis]].{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} In 1975, LaVey disbanded all grottos, leaving the organisation as a membership-based group that existed largely on paper.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=7|2a1=Lap|2y=2013|2p=84|3a1=Introvigne|3y=2016|3p=518}} He claimed that this had been necessary because the grottos had come to be dominated by social misfits who had not benefitted the church as a whole.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} In a private letter, he expressed frustration that despite growing church membership, "brain surgeons and Congressmen are still in short supply".{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=346–347}} He also announced that thenceforth all higher degrees in the church would be awarded in exchange for contributions of cash, real estate, or valuable art.{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1p=193|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=347}} Dissatisfied with these actions, in 1975, the high-ranking Church member Michael Aquino left to found his own Satanic organisation, the [[Temple of Set]],{{sfnm|1a1=Drury|1y=2003|1pp=193&ndash;194|2a1=Gallagher|2y=2006|2p=160|3a1=Schipper|3y=2010|3p=105}} which differed from LaVey's Church by adopting a belief that Satan literally existed.{{sfn|Schipper|2010|p=109}} According to Lap, from this point on Satanism became a "splintered and disorganized movement".{{sfn|Lap|2013|p=84}}

Between the abolition of the grotto system in 1975 and the establishment of the [[internet]] in the mid-1990s, ''The Satanic Bible'' remained the primary means of propagating Satanism.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}} During this period, a decentralized, anarchistic movement of Satanists developed that was shaped by many of the central themes that had pervaded LaVey's thought and which was expressed in ''The Satanic Bible''.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}} Lewis argued that in this community, ''The Satanic Bible'' served as a "quasi-scripture" because these independent Satanists were able to adopt certain ideas from the book while merging them with ideas and practices drawn from elsewhere.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=4}}

During the late 1980s, LaVey returned to the limelight, giving media interviews, attracting further celebrities, and reinstating the grotto system.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} In 1984 he separated from his wife, Diane Hegarty, and began a relationship with Blanche Barton,{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=512–513}} who was his personal assistant.{{sfn|Lewis|2001b|p=51}} In 1988 Hegarty brought a court case against LaVey, claiming that he she owned half of the church and LaVey's Black House. The court found in Hegarty's favour, after which LaVey immediately declared bankruptcy.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=377–378}} In May 1992, the ex-couple reached a settlement. The Black House was sold to a wealthy friend, the property developer Donald Werby, who agreed to allow LaVey to continue living at the residence for free.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=378}} Also in 1992, LaVey published his first book in twenty years, ''The Devil's Notebook''.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}} This was followed by the posthumous ''Satan Speaks'' in 1998, which included a foreword from the rock singer [[Marilyn Manson]],{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2p=516}} who was a priest in the church.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=384}}

In his final years, LaVey suffered from a heart condition, displayed increasing paranoia, and died in October 1997.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|2p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2pp=378–379}} In November, the church announced that it would subsequently be run by two High Priestesses of joint rank, Barton and LaVey's daughter [[Karla LaVey]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=516}} That same year, the church established an official website.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=140}} Barton attempted to purchase the Black House from Werby, but was unable to raise sufficient funds; the building had fallen into disrepair and was demolished in 2001, subsequently being replaced with an apartment block.{{sfnm|1a1=Introvigne|1y=2016|1p=516|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} A disagreement subsequently emerged between Barton and Karla, resulting in an agreement that Barton would retain legal ownership of the name and organization of the church while LaVey's personal belongings and copyrights would be distributed among his three children, Karla, Zeena, and Satan Xerxes.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Introvigne|2y=2016|2pp=516–517}} Barton stood down as High Priestess in 2002, although continued to chair the church's Council of Nine.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}} The headquarters of the church were then moved from San Francisco to New York, where [[Peter H. Gilmore]] was appointed the church's High Priest, and his wife Peggy Nadramia as its High Priestess.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}}

[[File:Peter H Gilmore 2 by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|left|Peter Gilmore, High Priest of the Church of Satan]]

After LaVey's death, conflict over the nature of Satanism intensified within the Satanic community.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=139}} At Halloween 1999 Karla established the [[First Satanic Church]], which uses its website to promote the idea that it represents a direct continuation of the original Church of Satan as founded by Anton LaVey.{{sfnm|1a1=Gallagher|1y=2006|1p=162|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} Other LaVeyan groups appeared elsewhere in the United States. An early member of the Church of Satan, John Dewey Allee, established his own First Church of Satan, claiming allegiance to LaVey's original teachings and professing that LaVey himself had deviated from them in later life.{{sfn|Gallagher|2006|p=162}} In 1986, Paul Douglas Valentine founded the New York City-based [[World Church of Satanic Liberation]], having recruited many of its members through [[Herman Slater]]'s Magickal Childe esoteric store. Its membership remained small and it was discontinued in 2011.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=517}} In 1991, the Embassy of Lucifer was established by the Canadian [[Tsirk Susuej]], which was influenced by LaVeyan teachings but held that Satan was a real entity.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=518}} Splinter groups from Susuej's organisation included the Embassy of Satan in [[Stewart, British Columbia]], and the Luciferian Light Group in [[Baltimore]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=518}} 

LaVeyan groups also cropped up elsewhere in the world, with a particular concentration in Scandinavia; most of these Scandinavian groups either split from the Church of Satan or never affiliated with it.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} These included the Svenska Satanistkyrkan and the Det Norske Sataniske Samfunn,{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} as well as the Prometheus Grotten of the Church of Satan which was established in Denmark in 1997 but which officially seceded in 2000.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=520}} A Satanic Church was also established in [[Estonia]] based on the LaVeyan model; it later renamed itself the [[Order of the Black Widow]].{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|pp=519–520}}

The Church of Satan became increasingly doctrinally-rigid and focused on maintaining the purity of LaVeyan Satanism.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} The church's increased emphasis on their role as the bearer of LaVey's legacy was partly a response to the growth in non-LaVeyan Satanists.{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=5}} Some Church members &ndash; including Gilmore{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=140}} &ndash; claimed that only they were the "real" Satanists and that those belonging to different Satanic traditions were "pseudo" Satanists.{{sfnm|1a1=Lewis|1y=2002|1p=5|2a1=van Luijk|2y=2016|2p=380}} After examining many of these claims on the church's website, Lewis concluded that it was "''obsessed'' with shoring up its own legitimacy by attacking the heretics, especially those who criticize LaVey".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=7}} Meanwhile, the church experienced an exodus of its membership in the 2000s, with many of these individuals establishing new groups online.{{sfn|Petersen|2013|p=139}} Although the church's public face had performed little ceremonial activity since the early 1970s, in June 2006 they held a Satanic 'High Mass' in Los Angeles to mark the church's fortieth birthday.{{sfn|Petersen|2012|pp=115&ndash;116}}

==Demographics==

Membership levels of the Church of Satan are hard to determine, as the organisation has not released such information.{{sfnm|1a1=Gardell|1y=2003|1p=287|2a1=Petersen|2y=2005|2p=430}} During its early years, the church claimed a membership of around 10,000, although defectors subsequently claimed that the number was only in the hundreds.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=344}} Membership was largely, although not exclusively, white.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|pp=369–370}} LaVey recognised this, suggesting that the church appealed particularly to white Americans because they lacked the strong sense of ethnic identity displayed by African-Americans and Hispanic Americans.{{sfn|van Luijk|2016|p=370}} The historian of religion [[Massimo Introvigne]] suggested that it had never had more than 1000 or 2000 members at its height, but that LaVeyan ideas had had a far greater influence through LaVey's books.{{sfn|Introvigne|2016|p=320}} Membership is gained by paying $225 and filling out a registration statement,{{sfn|Petersen|2005|p=430}} and thus initiates are bestowed with lifetime memberships and not charged annual fees.{{sfn|Gardell|2003|p=287}}

La Fontaine thought it likely that the easy availability of LaVey's writings would have encouraged the creation of various Satanic groups that were independent of the Church of Satan itself.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}} In ''The Black Flame'', a number of groups affiliated with the church have been mentioned, most of which are based in the United States and Canada although two groups were cited as having existed in New Zealand.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}} In his 2001 examination of Satanists, the sociologist [[James R. Lewis (scholar)|James R. Lewis]] noted that, to his surprise, his findings "consistently pointed to the centrality of LaVey's influence on modern Satanism".{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=5}} "Reflecting the dominant influence of Anton LaVey's thought", Lewis noted that the majority of those whom he examined were atheists or agnostics, with 60% of respondents viewing Satanism as a symbol rather than a real entity.{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=11}} 20% of his respondents described ''The Satanic Bible'' as the most important factor that attracted them to Satanism.{{sfn|Lewis|2001a|p=15}} Elsewhere, Lewis noted that few Satanists who weren't members of the Church of Satan would regard themselves as "orthodox LaVeyans".{{sfn|Lewis|2002|p=2}}

Examining the number of LaVeyan Satanists in Britain, in 1995 the religious studies scholar Graham Harvey noted that the Church of Satan had no organized presence in the country.{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}} He noted that LaVey's writings were widely accessible in British bookshops,{{sfn|Harvey|1995|p=290}} and La Fontaine suggested that there may have been individual Church members within the country.{{sfn|La Fontaine|1999|p=100}}

